<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910327-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>910327-0024.</DOCID><HL>   U.S., Longshoremen Settle   On Reforms in New York</HL><DATE>03/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><IN>MARINE TRANSPORTATION (MAR)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   NEW YORK -- The federal government and the InternationalLongshoremen's Association reached a settlement calling forbroad reforms, including supervised elections, at threeManhattan locals.   This is the second big settlement in the government'scivil racketeering suit aimed at purging the New York and NewJersey waterfront industry of alleged domination by organizedcrime. Last week, another local agreed to allow a courtappointee to oversee the union's affairs for three years.</LP><TEXT>   The suit, filed in Manhattan federal court in February1990, alleges a pattern of racketeering that includes murder,extortion, embezzlement of union funds and mail fraud. Amongthe defendants were six ILA locals and their executiveboards, 32 past and present union officials and numerousreputed organizedcrime figures. Also named arewaterfront-related businesses and two employer groupsconsisting of more than 150 shipping companies, warehouses,maintenance and repair companies, and others that serve theport.   In addition to supervised elections, the settlement calledfor Local 1909, whose members work on the trade show piers ofManhattan's West Side, to allow a monitor to oversee hiringoperations. The monitor will assure that the local's membersuse their own names and social security numbers and that nopaychecks are issued for fictitious services.</TEXT></DOC>